WEBVTT

00:02.263 --> 00:05.135
[indistinct chatter]

00:10.923 --> 00:12.534
- I still can't believe it.

00:12.621 --> 00:15.580
- Well, like you said,
this is science.

00:15.667 --> 00:16.973
And the numbers don't lie.

00:17.060 --> 00:19.802
- I did say that, didn't I?

00:19.889 --> 00:22.413
And the great thing is,
I'm right.

00:25.155 --> 00:28.115
I could get used to this.
- Me too.

00:28.202 --> 00:31.814
But until this is done,
we have to make sure nobody

00:31.901 --> 00:33.468
finds out what we're doing.

00:33.555 --> 00:34.556
- Of course.

00:34.643 --> 00:36.253
- I mean it.

00:36.340 --> 00:38.647
You have to promise.

00:38.734 --> 00:41.302
This stays between us.

00:41.389 --> 00:42.564
You swear?

00:42.651 --> 00:45.001
- Relax.
I'm not gonna say a word.

00:45.088 --> 00:48.657
[suspenseful music]

00:48.744 --> 00:50.441
It's late, and that was
a really long day.

00:50.528 --> 00:52.095
I'm gonna head home.

00:52.182 --> 00:53.401
See you tomorrow?

00:53.488 --> 00:54.445
- Bright and early.

00:56.621 --> 00:57.622
- Hmm.

00:57.709 --> 01:04.890
♪ ♪

01:17.033 --> 01:19.209
- Hmm. Look.

01:19.296 --> 01:22.125
Here's one
for swimming with horses.

01:22.212 --> 01:25.433
I mean, dolphins, I get,
but this sounds a little--

01:25.520 --> 01:27.739
- Precarious?
- Exactly.

01:27.826 --> 01:30.177
Oh, wait,
it's actually part of a deal

01:30.264 --> 01:32.048
to stay at a lodge
in Sun Valley.

01:32.135 --> 01:34.877
I wonder if you could pick
what time of year to go.

01:34.964 --> 01:36.270
- Remy.
- Hey.

01:36.357 --> 01:37.967
- Hey.
- Great to see you, man.

01:38.054 --> 01:39.969
- You too.
- Where the hell you been?

01:40.056 --> 01:40.926
- Ah, here and there.

01:41.013 --> 01:42.885
Teddy Beale, April Brooks.

01:42.972 --> 01:44.539
Teddy and I go way back.

01:44.626 --> 01:47.063
- All the way back to the
"Bright Lights, Big City" days.

01:47.150 --> 01:49.457
- Ah, late '80s. Wow.

01:49.544 --> 01:50.806
Sounds terrifying.

01:50.893 --> 01:52.112
- I plead the Fifth,
Your Honor.

01:52.199 --> 01:53.417
- [chuckles]
I bet you do.

01:53.504 --> 01:55.027
- Remy, I'll catch you later.

01:55.115 --> 01:56.551
Glad to see you out and about.
- You too.

02:00.555 --> 02:02.165
- Teddy Beale?

02:02.252 --> 02:03.819
Isn't he one of the Kennedys?

02:03.906 --> 02:06.126
- Not really--he's just
a cousin on the Bouvier side.

02:06.213 --> 02:07.083
- Oh, right.

02:07.170 --> 02:09.259
So this is your social circle?

02:09.346 --> 02:11.609
- It was, back when I worked
for my dad's investment firm,

02:11.696 --> 02:14.482
right out of college
through most of my 20s.

02:14.569 --> 02:16.527
- I mean, I knew that
you came late to the FBI,

02:16.614 --> 02:20.270
I just never realized
you took such a left turn.

02:20.357 --> 02:22.838
- Mm. I guess it was.

02:22.925 --> 02:25.623
But this is--
this is a good cause.

02:25.710 --> 02:28.278
And seeing you in this dress

02:28.365 --> 02:30.672
makes the whole night
worthwhile.

02:30.759 --> 02:33.544
- [chuckles]

02:33.631 --> 02:34.937
Thank you.

02:35.024 --> 02:36.721
- Not a fan of champagne?

02:36.808 --> 02:38.332
- You know, the bubbles
are pretty, but it's--

02:38.419 --> 02:39.681
it's a headache in a glass, so.

02:39.768 --> 02:40.682
- Let me get you
something else.

02:40.769 --> 02:42.162
- I'll do it.

02:42.249 --> 02:43.250
You go mingle
with your old friends.

02:43.337 --> 02:45.991
- All right, hurry back.
- Okay.

02:48.298 --> 02:50.648
Can I get a water
instead of this?

02:50.735 --> 02:51.997
Thank you.

02:54.826 --> 02:58.003
- Remy, I'm so glad you came.

02:58.090 --> 02:59.353
- Well, thanks
for including me.

02:59.440 --> 03:01.181
I don't get many
of these invites anymore.

03:01.268 --> 03:03.487
- Well, you do
when I'm cochairing an event.

03:03.574 --> 03:05.446
- This is amazing.
- Oh.

03:05.533 --> 03:07.274
Well, it's better than
what I used to do,

03:07.361 --> 03:10.712
which is basically
shopping, sex, and drugs.

03:10.799 --> 03:12.714
- Sex and drugs?
- [laughs]

03:12.801 --> 03:16.108
No, philanthropy is rewarding.

03:16.196 --> 03:18.154
- Well, you're obviously
very good at it.

03:18.241 --> 03:21.070
- Honestly,
you were an inspiration,

03:21.157 --> 03:23.551
your public service.

03:23.638 --> 03:24.682
Seriously.

03:35.215 --> 03:37.782
[tense music]

03:37.869 --> 03:45.050
♪ ♪

04:04.635 --> 04:07.247
- [gasping]

04:26.744 --> 04:27.876
- Hey.

04:27.963 --> 04:29.443
Are you okay?

04:29.530 --> 04:32.402
- [breathing raggedly]

04:37.407 --> 04:39.540
Oh, my God.

04:39.627 --> 04:41.498
Hang on. I'm gonna get help.

04:41.585 --> 04:42.847
- Help.

04:42.934 --> 04:49.289
♪ ♪

04:57.035 --> 04:58.602
- You're sure
you're okay with this?

04:58.689 --> 05:00.082
- Yeah, absolutely.
I've got two spare rooms.

05:00.169 --> 05:01.997
I could use help with the rent.
- Oh, wow.

05:02.084 --> 05:03.825
Hotel Hana's getting
a new tenant already?

05:03.912 --> 05:05.261
- It's not a hotel.

05:05.348 --> 05:06.480
Now, if you want someone
to make your bed

05:06.567 --> 05:08.046
and do your laundry,
don't bother.

05:08.133 --> 05:09.787
Otherwise, check it out
whenever you like.

05:09.874 --> 05:11.049
- Come on, guys. We're ready.

05:11.136 --> 05:14.139
- All right,
victim is Lydia Washburn.

05:14.226 --> 05:15.793
She survived having
her throat slit

05:15.880 --> 05:18.405
and digging herself out
of a shallow grave.

05:18.492 --> 05:20.145
Unfortunately, she died
earlier this morning

05:20.232 --> 05:21.886
on the operating table.

05:21.973 --> 05:24.411
- Hold on, hold on, she dug
herself out of her own grave?

05:24.498 --> 05:26.630
- Yeah, that's a first
for me too.

05:26.717 --> 05:28.676
She's single, no kids,
no family in the area.

05:28.763 --> 05:30.765
She worked as a geologist
at Columbia,

05:30.852 --> 05:31.766
and her phone's missing.

05:31.853 --> 05:33.289
- What makes this ours?

05:33.376 --> 05:35.160
- Because the last person
she was seen alive with

05:35.247 --> 05:36.858
is wanted
for stealing documents

05:36.945 --> 05:40.209
from the National Archives
in D.C.--this guy.

05:40.296 --> 05:42.472
Not enough for facial rec,
but notice that tattoo

05:42.559 --> 05:44.605
on the back of his neck?

05:44.692 --> 05:46.215
- 56 Rider.

05:46.302 --> 05:48.086
- 10 minutes after this
footage was posted,

05:48.173 --> 05:50.175
GSA sent this
from two weeks ago.

05:50.262 --> 05:52.308
Same build, same tattoo.

05:52.395 --> 05:54.658
That's our unsub
and probably our killer.

05:54.745 --> 05:55.964
- What kind of documents
did he steal?

05:56.051 --> 05:57.487
Were they classified?

05:57.574 --> 05:59.402
- Don't know yet,
but he also used

05:59.489 --> 06:01.665
a stolen government ID
to gain access.

06:01.752 --> 06:04.755
Between that and this killing,
NSA is on pins and needles.

06:04.842 --> 06:07.062
ERT is sending over
the victim's laptop.

06:07.149 --> 06:08.106
You start on that.
- Mm-hmm.

06:08.193 --> 06:09.151
- Kristin and Rae, head to D.C.

06:09.238 --> 06:10.413
Find out what he stole.

06:10.500 --> 06:11.719
Sheryll, you and I--

06:11.806 --> 06:13.155
- Headed to Columbia.
- Let's hit it.

06:13.242 --> 06:17.638
[suspenseful music]

06:17.725 --> 06:19.770
- Her students
are gonna be devastated.

06:19.857 --> 06:21.642
She was a terrific teacher.

06:21.729 --> 06:22.817
She published.

06:22.904 --> 06:24.601
She would have made tenure.

06:24.688 --> 06:26.647
- Do you know who she was
meeting with last night?

06:26.734 --> 06:29.214
- I know she was celebrating,
but I don't know who with.

06:29.301 --> 06:31.216
She had a side hustle.

06:31.303 --> 06:33.741
- What kind of a side hustle
does a geology professor have?

06:33.828 --> 06:35.917
- Well, she called it
her lottery ticket.

06:36.004 --> 06:39.311
There's only one way
geologists hit the lottery.

06:39.399 --> 06:42.053
- You mean she was making
extra money with speculators?

06:42.140 --> 06:45.622
- Yeah--oil, precious metals,
that kind of thing.

06:45.709 --> 06:47.842
We all do it once or twice
in our careers.

06:47.929 --> 06:49.409
Things seemed to be going
pretty well, though.

06:49.496 --> 06:50.932
- What was she speculating on?

06:51.019 --> 06:52.281
- I don't know.

06:52.368 --> 06:53.978
- You mean you didn't ask?

06:54.065 --> 06:55.415
- She'd have told me
if the mining rights

06:55.502 --> 06:58.635
had been locked down,
but in her shoes,

06:58.722 --> 06:59.767
I wouldn't have
said anything, either.

07:04.859 --> 07:07.470
- Sorry, every document we have
gets imaged and tagged,

07:07.557 --> 07:09.298
but these are so old,
it was under the old system.

07:09.385 --> 07:10.821
Sometimes it takes a while.
[computer beeps]

07:10.908 --> 07:13.041
There. Here we go.

07:13.128 --> 07:14.521
- So what are we
looking at here?

07:14.608 --> 07:16.348
- A set of pamphlets
created by

07:16.436 --> 07:17.741
the Knights
of the Golden Circle

07:17.828 --> 07:19.874
to promote their agenda.
- I've heard of them.

07:19.961 --> 07:22.659
Weren't they some kind
of white supremacy group?

07:22.746 --> 07:24.269
- Yes, they were a
secret society active

07:24.356 --> 07:26.446
during the American Civil War.

07:26.533 --> 07:28.056
In the event
the Confederacy lost,

07:28.143 --> 07:30.841
they intended to establish
a new pro-slavery nation.

07:30.928 --> 07:32.800
- What does that even mean?

07:32.887 --> 07:34.671
- Havana was supposed
to be the capital.

07:34.758 --> 07:37.195
It would have included
the American South, Mexico,

07:37.282 --> 07:39.023
parts of South America,
plus Cuba, Haiti,

07:39.110 --> 07:40.634
and the Dominican Republic.

07:40.721 --> 07:41.983
- All right, but the
Confederacy did lose.

07:42.070 --> 07:43.027
So what happened?

07:43.114 --> 07:44.464
- No one really knows.

07:44.551 --> 07:46.509
I guess they all just
went on with their lives.

07:49.686 --> 07:52.472
- Are these pamphlets
valuable at all?

07:52.559 --> 07:54.256
- They're not the
most iconic documents

07:54.343 --> 07:56.911
of the Golden Circle, but to
certain people, definitely.

07:56.998 --> 07:58.739
- What do you mean?

07:58.826 --> 08:00.610
- There were some pretty famous
people rumored to be members--

08:00.697 --> 08:02.960
John Wilkes Booth,
Nathan Bedford Forrest.

08:03.047 --> 08:05.180
It was like a who's who
of the anti-Union movement

08:05.267 --> 08:06.573
of their time.

08:06.660 --> 08:08.400
- And by anti-Union,
you mean racist?

08:08.488 --> 08:10.881
- I'm just saying,
this kind of memorabilia

08:10.968 --> 08:13.754
with the historical context,
unfortunately,

08:13.841 --> 08:15.451
it's probably worth a lot.
[phone ringing]

08:15.538 --> 08:18.367
- Like the Nazi paraphernalia
has value, right?

08:18.454 --> 08:20.630
- Awful, but yes,
exactly like that.

08:20.717 --> 08:22.153
- Right.

08:22.240 --> 08:24.547
- Okay, thanks.
We'll check it out.

08:24.634 --> 08:25.940
Hana found another
rare document theft

08:26.027 --> 08:27.898
at the University
of Pennsylvania library

08:27.985 --> 08:29.813
just two days
before the theft here.

08:29.900 --> 08:32.033
I mapped the dates
back to the Civil War.

08:32.120 --> 08:33.164
- Hmm, it looks like we're
making a detour to Philly.

08:33.251 --> 08:34.949
- Yes, it does.

08:35.036 --> 08:36.341
- Pick up some cheesesteaks
while we're there.

08:36.428 --> 08:38.866
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

08:38.953 --> 08:44.654
♪ ♪

08:44.741 --> 08:47.396
- Okay, we're almost there.

08:49.703 --> 08:50.921
- This better be worth it.

08:51.008 --> 08:51.879
- Oh, it is.

08:58.538 --> 09:00.365
- So this is what you've
been telling me about?

09:00.452 --> 09:01.453
- Wait till you see.

09:07.721 --> 09:10.811
[metal detector
chirping rapidly]

09:13.683 --> 09:15.424
- It's going crazy.

09:15.511 --> 09:17.948
I mean, it's just--it's all
over the place down here.

09:18.035 --> 09:19.776
- This is it. We found it.

09:23.606 --> 09:26.522
- [laughing]

09:29.394 --> 09:31.135
Well, it looks
like you did, Rosie.

09:31.222 --> 09:33.007
- What do you say, huh?

09:33.094 --> 09:35.009
It's enough proof for you?

09:35.096 --> 09:36.184
Can we get what we need now?

09:38.273 --> 09:41.015
- Heck, yeah.

09:41.102 --> 09:43.495
But you know this could
take a little while.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.410
- Not too long, though.

09:45.497 --> 09:47.630
- No, no, I'll get right on it.

09:51.765 --> 09:53.331
Who else knows about this?

09:53.418 --> 09:54.332
- Just us.

09:56.552 --> 09:58.206
- And you.

10:02.166 --> 10:04.429
- Whew.

10:04.516 --> 10:06.518
- The trip to Philly
paid off big time.

10:06.606 --> 10:09.086
The unsub used an expired
Pennsylvania driver's license

10:09.173 --> 10:10.697
to get into the UPenn library.

10:10.784 --> 10:12.568
His name is Leonard Oxridge.

10:12.655 --> 10:14.918
- Philly PD went
to the address on his license,

10:15.005 --> 10:16.354
but neighbors said he hadn't
lived there in years.

10:16.441 --> 10:18.226
- We got an address?

10:18.313 --> 10:20.097
- Yeah, I'm running
the databases now.

10:20.184 --> 10:22.273
- So Oxridge stole
a Civil War-era map

10:22.360 --> 10:25.886
of a rural area in Pennsylvania
known as Blackburn's Kill.

10:25.973 --> 10:27.670
- Is there a market
for maps like that?

10:27.757 --> 10:29.629
- I don't know,
the map is rare,

10:29.716 --> 10:31.326
but not particularly valuable.

10:31.413 --> 10:33.850
- I found something on
Lydia Washburn's hard drive.

10:33.937 --> 10:35.025
You know,
she recently conducted

10:35.112 --> 10:37.680
a series of core soil samples.

10:37.767 --> 10:39.943
The results show
the average 5.54 gram

10:40.030 --> 10:42.642
per ton of precious metal.

10:42.729 --> 10:44.339
- What kind of precious metal?

10:44.426 --> 10:45.993
- Gold.

10:46.080 --> 10:47.559
- Well, that must have been
her side hustle.

10:47.647 --> 10:49.649
- What does that mean,
5 grams per ton?

10:49.736 --> 10:51.389
- Well, anything
higher than 2 grams

10:51.476 --> 10:53.130
is considered a gold mine.

10:53.217 --> 10:55.698
So this suggests
that she found a stash

10:55.785 --> 10:57.700
of solid gold bars.
- Hmm.

10:57.787 --> 10:59.441
- Well, that sounds like
a motive for murder.

10:59.528 --> 11:01.356
- Yeah, definitely. Hold on.

11:01.443 --> 11:03.619
I just got a hit
on Leonard Oxridge.

11:03.706 --> 11:06.056
49 years old, divorced.

11:06.143 --> 11:09.016
Last known place of employment
was a mechanic in Morton, PA.

11:09.103 --> 11:10.234
- Does he have a record?

11:10.321 --> 11:12.149
- A few speeding tickets.

11:12.236 --> 11:14.848
Wait, he has military service.

11:14.935 --> 11:18.852
Pennsylvania National Guard,
56th Infantry, Striker Brigade.

11:18.939 --> 11:20.505
- Did you say 56th?

11:20.592 --> 11:22.899
- Yeah, just like the tattoo
on his neck.

11:22.986 --> 11:24.466
56 Rider.

11:24.553 --> 11:26.816
Guys, their motto is
"ride the lightning."

11:26.903 --> 11:27.991
This is our guy.

11:28.078 --> 11:29.471
- Do you have
a current address?

11:29.558 --> 11:31.603
- I'm looking in Pennsylvania.

11:31.691 --> 11:33.649
Nothing.
Let me check New York.

11:33.736 --> 11:35.433
Okay, an apartment in Brooklyn.

11:35.520 --> 11:37.435
I'm sending it to you now.
- On it.

11:37.522 --> 11:43.224
♪ ♪

11:43.311 --> 11:45.400
Leonard Oxridge?

11:45.487 --> 11:46.836
FBI.

11:46.923 --> 11:48.795
- [groaning] Help.

11:48.882 --> 11:52.450
[tense music]

11:52.537 --> 11:55.410
[groaning]

12:01.503 --> 12:03.331
- It's him.

12:03.418 --> 12:05.420
He's still alive.

12:05.507 --> 12:06.421
Here, take this.

12:06.508 --> 12:07.291
Hang in there.

12:07.378 --> 12:10.120
I'm getting help.

12:10.207 --> 12:11.556
Okay, stay with me, Leonard.

12:11.643 --> 12:13.471
Come on. Stay with me.

12:13.558 --> 12:15.125
Who did this to you, Leonard?

12:17.214 --> 12:18.694
Remy!

12:18.781 --> 12:19.956
- Got him!

12:20.043 --> 12:22.916
- [panting]

12:23.003 --> 12:29.270
♪ ♪

13:00.518 --> 13:03.391
[panting]

13:09.571 --> 13:12.879
- Sheryll, I lost him.

13:12.966 --> 13:14.794
How's Oxridge?

13:14.881 --> 13:16.056
- He didn't make it.

13:16.143 --> 13:19.102
- Damn it.

13:19.189 --> 13:20.843
Gonna have PD set a perimeter.

13:20.930 --> 13:22.802
You stay there and search
that place high and low.

13:22.889 --> 13:24.368
This guy was obviously
looking for something.

13:30.897 --> 13:31.767
- Far as I can tell,
Oxridge had no links

13:31.854 --> 13:33.813
to any white supremacy groups.

13:33.900 --> 13:36.424
- Okay, but I did find
some ties to other groups.

13:36.511 --> 13:39.209
He was active on a bunch
of treasure hunting websites.

13:39.296 --> 13:40.515
- What kind
of treasure hunters?

13:40.602 --> 13:42.343
- The kind looking
for Civil War gold

13:42.430 --> 13:44.867
at Blackburn's Kill
in Knox County, Pennsylvania.

13:44.954 --> 13:47.652
He was hooked on this
one story in particular.

13:47.739 --> 13:49.263
Check this out.

13:49.350 --> 13:52.788
In the summer of 1863,
a large transport of gold bars

13:52.875 --> 13:55.051
was being moved from
Wheeling, West Virginia,

13:55.138 --> 13:56.313
to the U.S. Mint
in Philadelphia

13:56.400 --> 13:57.619
in false-bottomed wagons

13:57.706 --> 14:00.317
to help finance
the Union war effort.

14:00.404 --> 14:02.145
- Sounds like the start
of a fairy tale.

14:02.232 --> 14:04.408
- I know it sounds crazy,
but bear with me.

14:04.495 --> 14:07.281
So this Lieutenant Castleton
hired a local guide.

14:07.368 --> 14:09.152
But right off the bat,
the lieutenant got sick,

14:09.239 --> 14:11.415
and the guide ran off
with the horses.

14:11.502 --> 14:13.156
Now the rest of the group
went to go and get help.

14:13.243 --> 14:15.071
The lieutenant
and Sergeant O'Rourke

14:15.158 --> 14:16.681
stayed behind with the gold.

14:16.768 --> 14:19.728
Now neither men or the gold
were ever seen again.

14:19.815 --> 14:22.339
- Surprise, surprise.

14:22.426 --> 14:23.340
I can't say I blame the guys
for taking off

14:23.427 --> 14:24.951
with the gold, though.
- Oh, yeah?

14:25.038 --> 14:26.387
- Oh, yeah.

14:26.474 --> 14:27.692
Brand-new beginning,
all lux, all the time?

14:27.779 --> 14:29.390
Come on.
[both chuckle]

14:29.477 --> 14:31.044
- So basically, we'd just
never see you again

14:31.131 --> 14:32.175
if you won the lottery?
- No.

14:32.262 --> 14:33.481
- And all this took place

14:33.568 --> 14:35.787
in Blackburn's Kill,
Pennsylvania?

14:35.875 --> 14:37.398
- Yeah, so they say.

14:37.485 --> 14:39.182
- Okay,
Knights of the Golden Circle.

14:39.269 --> 14:40.705
What do they have
to do with all this?

14:40.792 --> 14:42.403
- Here's the thing.

14:42.490 --> 14:44.448
There's no record
of any shipment of gold

14:44.535 --> 14:46.798
by the Union Army at that time,
and there's no military records

14:46.886 --> 14:49.932
of any Lieutenant Castleton
or a Sergeant O'Rourke.

14:50.019 --> 14:51.847
- So it is a fairy tale?

14:51.934 --> 14:54.850
- Maybe, but there is another
theory about the gold.

14:54.937 --> 14:56.896
Some people think it was the
Knights of the Golden Circle

14:56.983 --> 14:58.375
who transported it.

14:58.462 --> 15:01.204
Now the KGC used pamphlets
as coded directions

15:01.291 --> 15:03.250
for locations.

15:03.337 --> 15:04.773
- Pamphlets are
what Oxridge stole

15:04.860 --> 15:05.774
from the National Archive.

15:05.861 --> 15:07.384
- Mm-hmm.
- Right.

15:07.471 --> 15:08.864
- So we're looking
for someone who's trying

15:08.951 --> 15:11.562
to put a map together
to find the gold.

15:11.649 --> 15:14.957
Whoever hired Oxridge had him
steal those documents

15:15.044 --> 15:16.524
so no one else could
use them in the same way.

15:16.611 --> 15:18.613
- And Oxridge and Lydia
were killed

15:18.700 --> 15:20.354
so that they would be cut out
of their share of the find.

15:20.441 --> 15:22.965
- Greed is a very
powerful motive.

15:23.052 --> 15:26.534
- Guys, I found a stash
at Oxridge's apartment.

15:26.621 --> 15:29.015
Stolen pamphlets
and Civil War map,

15:29.102 --> 15:31.843
government ID he used
to get into the archive,

15:31.931 --> 15:34.237
and Oxridge's cell.

15:34.324 --> 15:36.239
There's over 20 calls
to a Tommy Thorne

15:36.326 --> 15:38.328
in Conroy, PA,
the last two days.

15:38.415 --> 15:39.851
- This is in Knox County?
- Yeah.

15:39.939 --> 15:41.027
- Did you try the number?

15:41.114 --> 15:42.680
- It goes straight
to voicemail.

15:42.767 --> 15:44.247
- Guess what
National Guard unit

15:44.334 --> 15:45.945
Tommy Thorne used to serve in?

15:46.032 --> 15:47.120
- 56th Striker Brigade.

15:47.207 --> 15:49.774
- Him and his brother, Buck.

15:49.861 --> 15:51.646
They've both got convictions
for trespassing with firearms.

15:51.733 --> 15:54.736
They're both on social media.

15:54.823 --> 15:56.390
- Oh, wow.

15:56.477 --> 15:58.044
Redneck treasure hunters.

15:58.131 --> 15:59.915
- They're connected to Oxridge,

16:00.002 --> 16:01.917
and they want those pamphlets
and maps,

16:02.004 --> 16:03.919
either to sell them
or to find that gold.

16:04.006 --> 16:05.442
- Alleged gold.

16:05.529 --> 16:07.531
- Whether that gold exists
or not doesn't matter.

16:07.618 --> 16:10.186
What matters is that
our unsub thinks it does.

16:10.273 --> 16:12.058
- Right.
- Guy's got gold fever.

16:12.145 --> 16:14.408
He's willing to kill anybody
that gets in his way.

16:14.495 --> 16:16.627
- Send that last known
to everyone's GPS.

16:16.714 --> 16:17.977
Let's roll.

16:18.064 --> 16:20.936
[suspenseful music]

16:21.023 --> 16:28.204
♪ ♪

16:44.916 --> 16:46.048
- Whoa!
- Whoa!

16:49.878 --> 16:52.011
- What the hell was that?

16:52.098 --> 16:54.100
- Got tripwires.

16:54.187 --> 16:56.015
- Place must be booby trapped.

16:58.539 --> 17:00.802
- Go slow.
Watch your feet, and split up.

17:00.889 --> 17:03.674
- Remy,
there's somebody out there.

17:05.937 --> 17:07.635
- Clear the house.

17:07.722 --> 17:09.245
Come on, Ray.

17:11.595 --> 17:13.597
You cover the back
in case we got a runner.

17:13.684 --> 17:15.251
I got the front.

17:15.338 --> 17:22.215
♪ ♪

17:31.137 --> 17:32.834
FBI!

17:32.921 --> 17:34.183
Drop your weapons!

17:34.270 --> 17:35.228
- Don't shoot.

17:35.315 --> 17:36.403
- Please don't kill us.

17:36.490 --> 17:43.366
♪ ♪

17:52.984 --> 17:54.334
- We were protecting ourselves.

17:54.421 --> 17:55.378
- If we'd have known
it was the Feds coming,

17:55.465 --> 17:56.858
we never would have
set those tripwires.

17:56.945 --> 17:58.425
- Protecting yourself from who?

17:58.512 --> 17:59.774
- We don't know.

17:59.861 --> 18:00.688
- We thought somebody
was coming for us,

18:00.775 --> 18:01.732
like they came for Lydia.

18:01.819 --> 18:02.907
- How do you know Lydia?

18:02.994 --> 18:04.170
- She's a geologist.

18:04.257 --> 18:06.172
She ran some
ground tests for us.

18:06.259 --> 18:07.347
- What kind of ground tests?

18:07.434 --> 18:08.478
- If I told you,
you wouldn't believe me.

18:08.565 --> 18:10.132
- Try us.

18:13.222 --> 18:15.094
- We found gold,
lost Civil War gold.

18:15.181 --> 18:16.965
It's why Lydia got killed.

18:17.052 --> 18:18.575
Somebody must have
found out about it.

18:18.662 --> 18:20.490
- Do you think that's why
Leonard Oxridge was murdered?

18:20.577 --> 18:23.189
- Lenny's dead?

18:23.276 --> 18:25.974
- Stabbed to death
in his apartment in Brooklyn.

18:26.061 --> 18:29.108
- Oh, man. Oh, man.

18:29.195 --> 18:30.761
You--you gotta protect us.

18:30.848 --> 18:31.806
- They'll be
coming for us next.

18:31.893 --> 18:33.068
What are we gonna do?

18:33.155 --> 18:34.809
- You knew Oxridge?
- Yeah.

18:34.896 --> 18:36.506
- Well, he's just
our army buddy.

18:36.593 --> 18:38.987
- We hired him
to find some stuff for us.

18:39.074 --> 18:40.031
- Stuff?

18:40.119 --> 18:41.163
What kind of stuff?

18:43.948 --> 18:46.603
Pamphlets written by the
Knights of the Golden Circle?

18:46.690 --> 18:48.344
Map of Blackburn's Kill?

18:48.431 --> 18:50.085
- We needed them
to find the cave.

18:50.172 --> 18:51.086
- But you didn't just hire him
to find those things, right?

18:51.173 --> 18:52.696
You hired him to steal them.

18:52.783 --> 18:53.741
- No.

18:53.828 --> 18:55.351
We--no.

18:57.527 --> 19:00.051
Okay, yeah.
We hired him to steal them.

19:00.139 --> 19:02.967
- We just wanted to be the
only ones who could make a map.

19:03.054 --> 19:04.578
We just wanted
to find the cave.

19:04.665 --> 19:06.319
- How long had you been
looking for it?

19:06.406 --> 19:08.277
- We grew up hearing
about the lost gold.

19:08.364 --> 19:10.627
When we were seven or eight,
Buck and me made a pact

19:10.714 --> 19:12.020
we'd find it, and we've been
looking for it ever since.

19:12.107 --> 19:13.761
Not full time or anything,

19:13.848 --> 19:17.417
but last year, we kicked it
into high gear.

19:17.504 --> 19:18.896
- I don't get it,
if you found the gold,

19:18.983 --> 19:20.507
why weren't you digging?

19:20.594 --> 19:22.552
- Well, we were about to,
and then we heard about Lydia.

19:22.639 --> 19:23.858
We got scared.

19:25.555 --> 19:30.343
- [sighs]
Okay, boys, let's take a hike.

19:30.430 --> 19:31.213
- Where to?

19:31.300 --> 19:33.128
- I want to see that cave.

19:33.215 --> 19:35.913
[suspenseful music]

19:36.000 --> 19:38.786
♪ ♪

19:38.873 --> 19:41.441
Stay with Barnes.

19:41.528 --> 19:48.448
♪ ♪

20:19.522 --> 20:21.089
- How much farther?

20:21.176 --> 20:23.831
- Cave's just up ahead
on the left.

20:23.918 --> 20:26.268
- We're almost there.

20:26.355 --> 20:28.314
- It's a long climb.
[chuckles]

20:28.401 --> 20:29.315
- Y'all okay?

20:31.578 --> 20:33.754
This is it.

20:33.841 --> 20:35.930
- Here?

20:36.017 --> 20:37.845
- So you two, Lydia,
and Oxridge are the only people

20:37.932 --> 20:38.846
who knew about this cave?

20:38.933 --> 20:40.282
- They never knew.

20:40.369 --> 20:41.588
Tommy and me had them
blindfolded real good

20:41.675 --> 20:42.937
the two times
they come up here.

20:43.024 --> 20:44.547
- Why'd you bring
them up twice?

20:44.634 --> 20:45.374
- Well,
once for the dirt samples,

20:45.461 --> 20:46.941
and when those came back good,

20:47.028 --> 20:48.421
she came up here
with the gravimeter.

20:48.508 --> 20:49.944
- What's that?

20:50.031 --> 20:51.772
- A super fancy metal detector,
crazy accurate.

20:51.859 --> 20:53.730
Cost, like, 100 grand.

20:53.817 --> 20:56.429
- Lydia was a professor,
so she had access to equipment

20:56.516 --> 20:57.995
like that through
the university.

20:58.082 --> 20:59.954
- Her gravimeter readings,
they're like a fingerprint.

21:00.041 --> 21:03.697
- That's just exactly how she
said it, like a fingerprint.

21:03.784 --> 21:05.568
- She said there's
8 and 1/2 to 9 tons--

21:05.655 --> 21:08.702
tons of metal
with a density of--

21:08.789 --> 21:09.964
what is it, Buck?

21:10.051 --> 21:12.140
- 19.3 grams
per centimeter cubed.

21:12.227 --> 21:13.315
- That's right.

21:13.402 --> 21:14.882
That's the exact density
of gold.

21:14.969 --> 21:17.058
That's what's in our cave,
a huge stash of gold bars

21:17.145 --> 21:18.755
all over the place.

21:18.842 --> 21:20.453
- That amount of gold
would mean a lot of money.

21:20.540 --> 21:23.020
- 500 million.
- Give or take.

21:24.152 --> 21:26.241
[metal clattering]

21:26.328 --> 21:28.678
- What the hell is that?

21:28.765 --> 21:30.898
Is somebody in there?

21:30.985 --> 21:33.030
[tense music]

21:33.117 --> 21:34.075
- What the actual--

21:34.162 --> 21:36.599
[gunshot]
[all gasp]

21:36.686 --> 21:37.905
- FBI!

21:40.864 --> 21:42.431
Come out with your hands up.

21:44.868 --> 21:46.174
Put that weapon down.

21:46.261 --> 21:47.828
Toss that weapon out.

21:47.915 --> 21:50.047
Toss it.

21:50.134 --> 21:57.272
♪ ♪

22:00.797 --> 22:02.103
- Sadie?

22:15.464 --> 22:16.465
- What the hell, Sadie?

22:16.552 --> 22:18.075
- Be quiet.

22:18.162 --> 22:19.294
- I take it you all
know each other.

22:19.381 --> 22:20.687
- Sadly, yes.

22:20.774 --> 22:22.123
- Went to high school
with her mom.

22:22.210 --> 22:23.298
- Could you be any more
of a whiny little bitch?

22:23.385 --> 22:24.908
- All right, easy.

22:24.995 --> 22:26.606
- What? I already apologized.

22:26.693 --> 22:28.782
If I'd have known it was the
Feds, I wouldn't have fired.

22:28.869 --> 22:30.349
- Wow, that is
the second time somebody

22:30.436 --> 22:31.654
has said that to us today.

22:31.741 --> 22:32.873
- So if it was
just Buck and me,

22:32.960 --> 22:34.222
you would have
blown our heads off?

22:34.309 --> 22:36.877
- Just protecting what's mine.
- Yours?

22:36.964 --> 22:38.748
- How'd you find our cave?
- Your cave?

22:38.835 --> 22:41.708
It's my cave. I cleared it out.

22:41.795 --> 22:43.797
- It was pretty clean
when we found it.

22:43.884 --> 22:46.452
- Yeah, that's 'cause
I got to it first, moron.

22:46.539 --> 22:48.758
There were all these bugs
and critters and rocks,

22:48.845 --> 22:50.281
and I got rid of them all.

22:50.369 --> 22:51.979
- Well,
what's the backpack for?

22:52.066 --> 22:53.676
- What do you think?

22:53.763 --> 22:55.765
Looking for gold,
just like you.

22:55.852 --> 22:57.811
[suspenseful music]

22:57.898 --> 22:59.987
- Give it to me.

23:00.074 --> 23:01.858
Come on. Give it to me.

23:01.945 --> 23:08.822
♪ ♪

23:11.128 --> 23:12.042
There's nothing in there.

23:12.129 --> 23:13.435
- Yeah.

23:13.522 --> 23:16.003
Well, I was kind
of interrupted.

23:16.090 --> 23:17.352
- Who else knows
about this cave?

23:17.439 --> 23:19.876
all:
Nobody.

23:19.963 --> 23:21.182
- This is starting to look like

23:21.269 --> 23:23.184
the worst-kept secret
in Knox County.

23:26.535 --> 23:28.494
What's all this?
- No idea.

23:28.581 --> 23:30.104
- Shouldn't you be in school?

23:30.191 --> 23:31.584
- We had a snow day.
- Yeah, real funny.

23:31.671 --> 23:33.063
- Yeah, what do
you know about it?

23:33.150 --> 23:34.369
You dropped out
in the fourth grade.

23:34.456 --> 23:35.762
- Shut up.
- No, you shut up.

23:35.849 --> 23:37.328
- That's enough, all of you.

23:37.416 --> 23:40.070
- Agent Quinn,
Treasury Department.

23:40.157 --> 23:41.158
- What's Treasury doing here?

23:41.245 --> 23:43.291
- Locking this area down.

23:43.378 --> 23:45.293
As of right now, nobody's
going in or out of that cave

23:45.380 --> 23:46.729
except me or my team.

23:46.816 --> 23:48.209
- Oh, I think
you might be mistaken.

23:48.296 --> 23:50.037
This is state property,
not federal.

23:50.124 --> 23:51.865
You have no jurisdiction.

23:51.952 --> 23:54.171
- If there's gold in there,
it's from the U.S. Mint,

23:54.258 --> 23:55.956
and it's federal property.

23:56.043 --> 23:59.046
And this federal warrant
gives me, and only me,

23:59.133 --> 24:00.569
the right to excavate
that cave.

24:00.656 --> 24:01.962
- Hey, wait a minute.

24:02.049 --> 24:03.616
You can't just waltz
in here and call dibs.

24:03.703 --> 24:05.835
- What's she doing?
- Taking over the cave.

24:05.922 --> 24:07.707
- Uh-uh.
- Who do you think you are?

24:07.794 --> 24:09.883
- I'm the United States
government.

24:09.970 --> 24:12.451
Get them out of here.

24:12.538 --> 24:13.452
- What the hell are you doing?

24:13.539 --> 24:14.931
- My job.

24:15.018 --> 24:17.194
- We need eyes in those woods,
on that cave.

24:17.281 --> 24:18.892
We got an unsub in the wind.

24:18.979 --> 24:20.589
This guy is a ruthless killer

24:20.676 --> 24:22.156
who thinks there's gold
up there.

24:22.243 --> 24:23.810
That's where
we're gonna catch him.

24:23.897 --> 24:26.987
- It isn't your problem
anymore, Agent Scott.

24:27.074 --> 24:29.163
Treasury's taken over the case.

24:29.250 --> 24:31.078
- You may know how
to execute a warrant,

24:31.165 --> 24:33.384
but you don't know the first
thing about catching a killer.

24:33.472 --> 24:35.735
- I'm not interested
in catching a killer.

24:35.822 --> 24:38.738
I'm interested
in what's in that cave.

24:38.825 --> 24:41.088
Look, if you have a problem,
take it up with your SAC.

24:41.175 --> 24:42.785
She'll confirm.

24:42.872 --> 24:45.484
But right now,
no one's going in or out,

24:45.571 --> 24:48.051
not your unsub and not the FBI.

24:48.138 --> 24:50.271
- You do what you have to do.

24:50.358 --> 24:51.838
So will I.

24:54.580 --> 24:56.233
Where are your parents?

24:56.320 --> 24:58.105
- Never met my daddy.

24:58.192 --> 24:59.802
Mom died a year ago.

24:59.889 --> 25:02.022
I'm an orphan
of the opioid epidemic.

25:02.109 --> 25:03.414
- Oh, please.

25:03.502 --> 25:05.591
It ain't as tragic as that.

25:05.678 --> 25:06.896
She lives
with her grandparents.

25:12.032 --> 25:15.035
- Sadie's been living with us
just over a year now,

25:15.122 --> 25:17.298
since her mama died.

25:17.385 --> 25:20.214
- What were you doing
up there in that cave?

25:20.301 --> 25:22.782
- Nothing, just looking around.

25:22.869 --> 25:25.262
- She told us the three of you
are the ones who found it.

25:29.615 --> 25:31.181
- Oh, you did, did you?

25:31.268 --> 25:32.748
- Well, I had to.

25:32.835 --> 25:34.228
Buck and Tommy were up there.

25:34.315 --> 25:35.621
They think it's theirs.

25:35.708 --> 25:37.013
- Well, they're wrong.

25:37.100 --> 25:39.363
- Well, they were saying
that they found it first,

25:39.450 --> 25:40.408
when we're the ones
who've been prospecting

25:40.495 --> 25:42.628
up there for over a year.

25:42.715 --> 25:44.412
We found it. We cleaned it out.

25:44.499 --> 25:46.327
- Hear that, Rosie?

25:46.414 --> 25:47.502
It's a good thing we dotted
all our Is and crossed our Ts.

25:47.589 --> 25:49.069
- Sure is.

25:49.156 --> 25:51.506
We locked down our claim
through the proper channels.

25:51.593 --> 25:53.203
- How'd you do that?

25:53.290 --> 25:54.770
- That land up there
is the property

25:54.857 --> 25:56.598
of the Commonwealth
of Pennsylvania.

25:56.685 --> 25:58.687
So before we even
touched anything,

25:58.774 --> 26:01.429
we made sure to get a permit
to clean out that cave from the

26:01.516 --> 26:03.474
Department of Conservation
of Natural Resources.

26:03.562 --> 26:05.781
- Now we're just waiting
on the permit to excavate.

26:05.868 --> 26:07.000
It's still pending.

26:07.087 --> 26:08.567
- None of that matters now.

26:08.654 --> 26:09.872
The Feds are up there.

26:09.959 --> 26:11.221
They're taking everything
for themselves.

26:11.308 --> 26:12.396
- What?
- Mm-hmm.

26:12.483 --> 26:14.181
- She's right.

26:14.268 --> 26:16.226
The Treasury Department
came in today with a warrant.

26:16.313 --> 26:18.402
They're the ones that'll
be excavating the cave.

26:18.489 --> 26:20.535
- So what does that mean
for our contract?

26:20.622 --> 26:22.276
- It means we're screwed,
Granddad.

26:22.363 --> 26:23.799
I told you, we should have just
started digging.

26:23.886 --> 26:25.758
- This is the government,
Sadie.

26:25.845 --> 26:28.021
We have a contract,
and they'll have to honor it.

26:28.108 --> 26:31.024
They'll owe us
our finder's fee.

26:31.111 --> 26:33.156
- Who gave you
a finder's fee agreement?

26:36.029 --> 26:39.032
- Got it here someplace,
just like.

26:39.119 --> 26:42.035
[suspenseful music]

26:42.122 --> 26:43.123
Yeah.

26:45.691 --> 26:49.608
- 25% of whatever
we find in there.

26:49.695 --> 26:52.611
- This is signed by a ranger.

26:52.698 --> 26:55.744
- That's right, a government
official, Toby Medina.

26:55.831 --> 26:57.485
- Does he know
where the cave is?

26:57.572 --> 26:58.660
- Yep, we had to show him
where it was

26:58.747 --> 27:00.314
before he give us that permit.

27:00.401 --> 27:01.532
- Do you have
an address for Toby?

27:01.620 --> 27:02.925
- Yeah,
I'm sending it to you now.

27:03.012 --> 27:03.970
- Take Ray with you
to the Rangers office,

27:04.057 --> 27:05.536
see what they know.

27:05.624 --> 27:07.016
I'll have Kristin and Barnes
meet you at his house.

27:07.103 --> 27:08.409
- Thanks.

27:08.496 --> 27:14.720
♪ ♪

27:14.807 --> 27:17.810
- Sure, as park rangers,
we can grant or deny permits

27:17.897 --> 27:19.333
for all kinds
of different activities

27:19.420 --> 27:21.248
on state-owned land.

27:21.335 --> 27:22.989
- What about granting something
like a finder's fee

27:23.076 --> 27:24.686
for any precious metals
that a private citizen

27:24.773 --> 27:26.253
finds on state-owned land?

27:26.340 --> 27:28.211
- A finder's fee?

27:28.298 --> 27:29.822
- Yeah, one of your rangers,
Toby Medina,

27:29.909 --> 27:32.172
granted Desmond
and Rose Daley a permit

27:32.259 --> 27:33.477
to excavate Blackburn's Kill.

27:33.564 --> 27:34.957
- Yeah, he also
gave them a document

27:35.044 --> 27:36.959
guaranteeing them
a 25% finder's fee

27:37.046 --> 27:38.831
for any gold they may dig up.

27:40.441 --> 27:44.619
- No, that's not--

27:44.706 --> 27:45.968
are you sure about that?

27:46.055 --> 27:48.144
- Yeah, uh,
that's his signature, right?

27:51.278 --> 27:53.846
- Yes, it is, but this
is not something we can do.

27:53.933 --> 27:55.935
I don't even know who could.

27:56.022 --> 27:57.937
I mean, the governor's office,
maybe, but--

27:58.024 --> 27:59.286
- All right, so we're
gonna need to talk to Toby.

27:59.373 --> 28:00.287
Is he here now?

28:02.332 --> 28:04.117
- No, he's been out
on compassionate leave

28:04.204 --> 28:05.074
for a couple weeks.

28:05.161 --> 28:07.773
His mom died.

28:07.860 --> 28:10.079
But he's back on Monday.

28:10.166 --> 28:12.952
- Hmm.
No, mother died in 2016.

28:15.302 --> 28:17.086
- We're too late. He's gone.

28:17.173 --> 28:18.697
- This guy left everything.

28:18.784 --> 28:20.568
- Looks like these will tie him
to the murders

28:20.655 --> 28:23.484
of both Lydia Washburn
and Leonard Oxridge.

28:25.747 --> 28:29.185
- Look at this, Lydia's phone.

28:29.272 --> 28:31.187
- Toby didn't even bother
trying to get rid of any of it.

28:31.274 --> 28:33.363
- No, 'cause he's planning
to disappear

28:33.450 --> 28:35.670
with whatever gold he can get
out of that cave.

28:35.757 --> 28:37.324
- He knew about the cave.

28:37.411 --> 28:39.195
He must have known
who was circling the gold.

28:39.282 --> 28:41.023
He strung Rose
and Desmond along,

28:41.110 --> 28:42.982
claiming that their
permits were pending,

28:43.069 --> 28:45.027
and then slowed
the Thorne brothers down

28:45.114 --> 28:47.116
by killing Lydia and Oxridge.

28:47.203 --> 28:50.119
- All he needed to do was
get in there first,

28:50.206 --> 28:51.686
take what he could,
and get away.

28:51.773 --> 28:54.167
- But he wasn't counting
on Agent Quinn.

28:54.254 --> 28:56.343
- Right.
- So what's his plan B?

28:56.430 --> 28:57.736
- Well, if he's smart,
he'll run,

28:57.823 --> 28:59.694
try not to get arrested
for murder.

28:59.781 --> 29:02.436
- No, he's too deep into trying
to get his hands on that gold.

29:02.523 --> 29:05.047
- As long as Toby's out there,
the Daleys, Sadie,

29:05.134 --> 29:08.747
the Thornes could all
still be targets.

29:08.834 --> 29:11.271
Put deputies on their houses
for protection

29:11.358 --> 29:13.055
and one here in case
he comes back.

29:13.142 --> 29:14.404
- All right, I'll put
a BOLO out on Toby's car,

29:14.491 --> 29:16.058
get Hana to track
his credit cards.

29:16.145 --> 29:17.712
- We're going back
to Blackburn's Kill.

29:19.583 --> 29:20.759
I'm telling you right now,

29:20.846 --> 29:22.325
this guy is desperate
and dangerous,

29:22.412 --> 29:23.631
and I got a really bad
feeling that he's gonna try

29:23.718 --> 29:25.111
to get past Quinn's perimeter.

29:25.198 --> 29:26.590
It's gonna be a long night.

29:26.677 --> 29:33.597
♪ ♪

30:19.774 --> 30:21.384
- Hey, Sadie.

30:21.471 --> 30:24.039
- Hey, Toby.

30:24.126 --> 30:26.868
- Where you going?

30:26.955 --> 30:29.349
- No place.

30:29.436 --> 30:35.921
♪ ♪

30:51.588 --> 30:53.590
[tense music]

30:53.677 --> 30:54.548
- Sadie's gone!

30:54.635 --> 30:56.028
- We just heard.

30:56.115 --> 30:57.464
- You have to help us find her.

30:57.551 --> 30:58.552
- It's gonna be all right.
We're gonna find her.

30:58.639 --> 31:00.423
Stay calm, okay?

31:00.510 --> 31:02.208
- Where are the deputies
who were watching the house?

31:02.295 --> 31:03.949
- They're searching
out back with Des.

31:04.036 --> 31:06.255
They swear nobody came on
to the property.

31:06.342 --> 31:07.430
- Her bike's gone.
- That's a good thing.

31:07.517 --> 31:08.954
It means she probably
left on her own.

31:09.041 --> 31:11.652
- Okay, where would she go?

31:11.739 --> 31:13.349
- The cave, maybe.

31:13.436 --> 31:15.525
I mean, if anybody could
sneak up there, it's her.

31:15.612 --> 31:17.876
- Why would she do that?
It's all locked down.

31:17.963 --> 31:19.094
She knows she's not
supposed to go up there.

31:19.181 --> 31:20.356
- Rosie, I don't know.
I don't know.

31:20.443 --> 31:21.923
The gold makes you do
crazy things.

31:22.010 --> 31:23.098
- All right,
we're gonna handle it.

31:23.185 --> 31:24.447
You want to cover that?
- Yeah.

31:24.534 --> 31:25.622
- We're on it.
Where else would Sadie go?

31:25.709 --> 31:27.537
- Her phone keeps going
straight to voicemail.

31:27.624 --> 31:30.497
She always answers, always.
- Rose, look at me. Think.

31:30.584 --> 31:31.846
Does she have a boyfriend?
Does she have friends?

31:31.933 --> 31:32.891
- No, no, no, she spends
all her free time

31:32.978 --> 31:34.327
looking for the gold.

31:34.414 --> 31:35.894
- The old house.

31:35.981 --> 31:37.634
- Old house?
- Her mom's.

31:37.721 --> 31:39.288
It's Sadie's now.

31:39.375 --> 31:41.029
Sometimes she goes there
when she's feeling sad.

31:41.116 --> 31:41.856
- Okay.

31:41.943 --> 31:42.901
- [grunts]
- [yelps]

31:42.988 --> 31:44.598
- I am not messing around.

31:44.685 --> 31:48.167
I know it's here, so tell me
where you stashed it.

31:48.254 --> 31:50.169
- I told you, I don't know
what you're talking about!

31:52.475 --> 31:56.392
- You think you're so smart,
but you're not.

31:56.479 --> 31:59.091
I got you on tape going in
and out of that cave,

31:59.178 --> 32:01.136
in with an empty backpack,

32:01.223 --> 32:04.096
out with a full, heavy one
nine, ten times.

32:04.183 --> 32:05.662
- Screw you!
[gunshot]

32:05.749 --> 32:07.099
[yelps]

32:07.186 --> 32:09.144
- Get up.

32:09.231 --> 32:10.841
Get up.

32:10.929 --> 32:12.669
- FBI! Drop your weapon.

32:12.756 --> 32:16.412
♪ ♪

32:16.499 --> 32:19.676
- Toby, you don't want
to do this.

32:19.763 --> 32:21.765
- She took it!

32:21.852 --> 32:23.637
She took the gold, and she
stashed it here somewhere.

32:23.724 --> 32:24.986
- No, I didn't.

32:25.073 --> 32:25.639
He doesn't know what
he's talking about.

32:25.726 --> 32:28.511
- Yes, I do.

32:28.598 --> 32:30.905
Tell them.

32:30.992 --> 32:33.690
- Let her go, Toby.

32:33.777 --> 32:35.649
She's just a kid.

32:38.086 --> 32:40.132
- I have her on video
from my trail cam

32:40.219 --> 32:42.090
taking gold out of that cave.

32:42.177 --> 32:43.962
- Take the shot when
you got it, Ray.

32:44.049 --> 32:46.442
- It's not true.
- Shut up! Shut up!

32:46.529 --> 32:48.140
- I believe you, Toby.

32:50.142 --> 32:51.970
But this isn't gonna
solve anything.

32:55.930 --> 32:58.063
- Put the gun down.

32:58.150 --> 33:01.892
- It's too late for that.

33:01.980 --> 33:04.243
There is gold right here.

33:07.246 --> 33:09.117
Make her--
make her show me where it is.

33:11.076 --> 33:12.468
Make her show me where it is.

33:12.555 --> 33:13.774
- He's crazy.
- And I'll let her go.

33:13.861 --> 33:15.341
- He dragged me out here.

33:15.428 --> 33:17.952
- No, no!

33:18.039 --> 33:19.432
I followed you out here.

33:19.519 --> 33:20.128
- I don't know what
he's talking about.

33:20.215 --> 33:22.478
- Yes, you do! Stop lying!

33:22.565 --> 33:24.741
[gunshot]

33:24.828 --> 33:31.705
♪ ♪

33:41.758 --> 33:43.064
- What a circus.

33:43.151 --> 33:44.892
[reporters chattering]

33:44.979 --> 33:46.763
- What the hell is going on?

33:46.850 --> 33:48.722
- The excavation was a bust.

33:48.809 --> 33:51.551
We spent all night looking,
but there's no gold in there.

33:51.638 --> 33:54.728
We dug so far down,
we penetrated the water table

33:54.815 --> 33:55.859
and flooded the cave.

33:55.946 --> 33:57.426
- That's not possible.

33:57.513 --> 33:58.862
That gravimeter reading
is like a fingerprint.

33:58.949 --> 34:00.647
- How do you explain that?

34:00.734 --> 34:02.431
- Well, it looks like
the good people of Knox County

34:02.518 --> 34:03.867
think you're a liar.

34:03.954 --> 34:06.566
- They're entitled
to their alternative facts

34:06.653 --> 34:08.089
if that's what they want.

34:08.176 --> 34:09.221
- Maybe they just know
when they're being gaslit.

34:09.308 --> 34:11.049
- Not to mention
a bunch of people

34:11.136 --> 34:13.834
saw armored trucks going up
and down the hill all night.

34:13.921 --> 34:17.446
- Empty trucks because
there was no gold to remove.

34:17.533 --> 34:20.058
It was a nice story,
but that's all it was.

34:20.145 --> 34:21.494
This whole thing was a myth.

34:21.581 --> 34:23.365
- Well, while you've been
digging in the dirt,

34:23.452 --> 34:25.367
we've been getting
real results.

34:25.454 --> 34:28.849
We caught that killer
and saved a kid.

34:28.936 --> 34:30.851
Stolen pamphlets and map.

34:30.938 --> 34:32.809
Since this is your case now,
you can return these

34:32.896 --> 34:34.028
to the National Archive.

34:34.115 --> 34:37.031
[pensive music]

34:37.118 --> 34:40.687
♪ ♪

34:40.774 --> 34:42.689
- What's in the envelope?
Is that the treasure map?

34:42.776 --> 34:44.430
- Why are you lying?

34:44.517 --> 34:45.953
- Did you confiscate the gold
for the Treasury Department?

34:46.040 --> 34:47.911
- You can't hide
what you're doing!

34:47.998 --> 34:50.349
- We need some answers.
- Everybody saw those trucks.

34:50.436 --> 34:51.741
You can't hide
what you're doing.

34:51.828 --> 34:52.873
- Hey, you okay?

34:52.960 --> 34:55.745
- Yeah.

34:55.832 --> 34:58.922
- So what Toby said about
having a camera planted

34:59.009 --> 35:02.100
on the trail, is that true?

35:02.187 --> 35:04.102
- I don't know, but I doubt it.

35:04.189 --> 35:05.842
The man's a psycho and a liar.

35:05.929 --> 35:07.627
- Yeah, he is.

35:07.714 --> 35:09.063
- Plus, I was up there
enough looking for the cave.

35:09.150 --> 35:10.586
I'm sure I would have seen it.

35:10.673 --> 35:13.502
- So let's say for giggles,
it is true.

35:13.589 --> 35:16.940
Would it show you taking gold
out of that cave?

35:19.552 --> 35:20.683
- How could it?
You heard the lady.

35:20.770 --> 35:22.250
There wasn't any gold.

35:22.337 --> 35:24.296
How could I steal something
that was never there?

35:26.515 --> 35:28.474
- You're a smart cookie, Sadie.

35:28.561 --> 35:35.133
♪ ♪

35:38.266 --> 35:39.833
- Well, that sounds
like a crazy case.

35:39.920 --> 35:41.922
- It was.

35:42.009 --> 35:44.185
Hey, do you ever think about

35:44.272 --> 35:45.534
what you'd do
if you won the lottery?

35:45.621 --> 35:49.495
Like, the big one,
100 million bucks.

35:49.582 --> 35:50.887
- I've fantasized
about it, yeah.

35:50.974 --> 35:51.627
Doesn't everybody?

35:51.714 --> 35:53.499
- I guess.

35:53.586 --> 35:56.676
But is there such a thing
as too much money?

35:56.763 --> 35:59.853
So much that it takes the fun
out of everything?

35:59.940 --> 36:03.422
- You know, money's freedom,
especially to people

36:03.509 --> 36:05.685
who've never had it before, so.
- Hmm.

36:05.772 --> 36:07.208
- Is this how
you spent your day,

36:07.295 --> 36:09.384
thinking about
being filthy rich?

36:09.471 --> 36:13.214
- Part of it,
and part of it dealing

36:13.301 --> 36:15.303
with what it can do to people.

36:18.611 --> 36:22.397
Anyway, I can think
of better ways

36:22.484 --> 36:24.921
to spend my time right now.

36:25.008 --> 36:25.922
[phone ringing]

36:26.009 --> 36:27.228
Oh.

36:30.318 --> 36:32.799
Doorman.

36:32.886 --> 36:34.757
Hey, Georgie. What's up?

36:34.844 --> 36:35.932
Okay.

36:36.019 --> 36:37.673
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

36:37.760 --> 36:39.632
Thanks, Georgie.

36:39.719 --> 36:41.677
Package, I gotta sign for it.
- Oh, no worries.

36:41.764 --> 36:43.853
You know, I'm gonna get out
of these clothes.

36:43.940 --> 36:45.942
- Oh, I like that idea.

36:46.029 --> 36:48.249
[both chuckle]

36:55.822 --> 36:57.258
Fiona?

36:57.345 --> 36:59.434
Wow, I thought you were
the delivery man.

36:59.521 --> 37:01.044
- Delivery? Yes.

37:01.131 --> 37:02.655
Man? I take no offense.

37:02.742 --> 37:04.787
Mind if I come in?

37:04.874 --> 37:07.442
Oh, amazing.

37:07.529 --> 37:08.617
- Thanks.

37:08.704 --> 37:10.880
- Seriously,
look at this place.

37:10.967 --> 37:13.622
You still got it, don't you?

37:13.709 --> 37:15.015
Here.

37:15.102 --> 37:16.321
- What's this?

37:16.408 --> 37:18.932
- You won your
silent auction item.

37:19.019 --> 37:21.674
- You know, you could have
just popped it in the mail.

37:21.761 --> 37:24.851
- Oh, I know,
but I was so excited you

37:24.938 --> 37:26.635
came the other night, I just--

37:26.722 --> 37:28.028
I wanted to give it
to you personally.

37:32.075 --> 37:33.990
Oh.

37:34.077 --> 37:34.991
Oh, I'm sorry.

37:35.078 --> 37:36.384
I mean, I didn't realize.

37:36.471 --> 37:37.690
- No, no, no, no, it's okay.

37:37.777 --> 37:39.953
April Brooks,
this is Fiona Paley.

37:40.040 --> 37:42.869
Fiona was the cochair
of the gala the other night.

37:42.956 --> 37:47.177
She was kind enough
to hand-deliver my auction win.

37:47.265 --> 37:49.397
- Hi, and congratulations.

37:49.484 --> 37:51.834
That was a lovely event.
- Thank you.

37:51.921 --> 37:54.010
And I wish I would have
met you the other night.

37:56.709 --> 37:58.754
Anyway, I should
have called first.

37:58.841 --> 38:01.279
It was lovely
to meet you, April.

38:01.366 --> 38:03.193
- You too.
- And congratulations.

38:03.281 --> 38:05.021
Remy, I have to run.

38:09.591 --> 38:11.201
- So what'd you get?
- I don't know.

38:13.421 --> 38:16.729
Three nights
at the Sun Valley Lodge.

38:16.816 --> 38:18.470
- That swimming
with horses thing?

38:18.557 --> 38:19.862
- Mm-hmm.

38:19.949 --> 38:21.473
- That bid was
at 11 grand when we left.

38:21.560 --> 38:23.953
How high did you go?
- Hmm.

38:24.040 --> 38:26.565
It's for a worthy cause.

38:26.652 --> 38:29.655
- Is it the cause,
or is it Fiona?

38:29.742 --> 38:30.873
- April, come on.

38:30.960 --> 38:32.527
She's just an old friend.

38:32.614 --> 38:34.834
- Yeah, okay.
- We talked about this.

38:34.921 --> 38:37.271
No baggage, no commitments,
no craziness.

38:37.358 --> 38:38.751
Let's just do us.
- I know.

38:38.838 --> 38:40.405
You have your past,
I have mine,

38:40.492 --> 38:41.710
and never the twain shall meet.

38:41.797 --> 38:43.538
- Exactly.

38:43.625 --> 38:45.323
- Yeah.

38:45.410 --> 38:47.499
- You're not mad, are you?

38:47.586 --> 38:48.978
Oh, come on. Don't be mad.

38:49.065 --> 38:51.981
- I'm not mad.

38:52.068 --> 38:54.549
- Then where are you going?

38:57.944 --> 39:00.860
[tense music]

39:00.947 --> 39:07.519
♪ ♪

39:56.394 --> 39:59.092
[tense music]

39:59.179 --> 40:06.099
♪ ♪

40:15.500 --> 40:17.066
[wolf howls]
